Remove outliers from the dataset using Combined Method (Z-score and IQR)¶

IQR is based on percentiles and is not affected by the mean and standard deviation. It is useful in cases of skewed data. Z-score is based on standard deviation and is affected by the mean and standard deviation. It is useful in cases of normal distribution.

In [ ]:
# Calculate Z-scores
z_scores = np.abs(stats.zscore(df._get_numeric_data()))
df_no_outliers_z = df[(z_scores < 3).all(axis=1)]

# Calculate IQR
Q1 = df.quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df.quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1
df_no_outliers_iqr = df[~((df < (Q1 - 1.5 * IQR)) | (df > (Q3 + 1.5 * IQR))).any(axis=1)]

# Combine both methods
df_no_outliers = df_no_outliers_z.index.intersection(df_no_outliers_iqr.index)
df_final = df.loc[df_no_outliers]

Another Method using datasist library

In [ ]:
outlier_indices = detect_outliers(df, 0, df.columns)
#Remove outliers
#df_cleaned = df.drop(outlier_indices)
#Relplace outliers with median values
df_cleaned = df.copy()
for feature in df.columns:
    median = df[feature].median()
    df_cleaned.loc[outlier_indices, feature] = median
#Replace outliers with winsorized values
df_cleaned = df.copy()
for feature in df.columns:
    df_cleaned[feature] = mstats.winsorize(df[feature], limits=[0.05, 0.05])

T-Statistic: -42.827577964296296
P-Value: 0.0

T-Statistic: -42.827577964296296 The t-statistic measures the difference in means between the two groups relative to the variability within each group. In this case, the negative value indicates that the mean obesity level in the heart attack group is lower than in the diabetes group.

P-Value: 0.0 The p-value represents the probability of observing the t-statistic given that the null hypothesis is true (i.e., there is no difference between the groups). A p-value of 0.0 suggests extremely strong evidence against the null hypothesis. Therefore, we can conclude that there is a significant difference in obesity levels between individuals with heart attacks and those with diabetes.

overall_diabetes_prevalence = df['diabetes'].mean()

# Print the overall prevalence rates

print(f"Overall Prevalence of Diabetes: {overall_diabetes_prevalence}")

# Assess the distribution of heart attacks and diabetes across demographic and risk factor categories
demographic_columns = ['age', 'gender']
risk_factor_columns = ['Obesity', 'Cholesterol', 'Blood Pressure']

for column in demographic_columns:
    group_counts = df.groupby(column)[['Heart Attack Risk', 'diabetes']].mean()
    print(f"\nPrevalence of Heart Attacks and Diabetes by {column}:")
    print(group_counts)

for column in risk_factor_columns:
    group_counts = df.groupby(column)[['Heart Attack Risk', 'diabetes']].mean()
    print(f"\nPrevalence of Heart Attacks and Diabetes by {column}:")
    print(group_counts)

# Helper Function to get ISO Alpha-3 country code from country name
def get_country_code(country_name):
    try:
        country = pycountry.countries.get(name=country_name)
        return country.alpha_3
    except:
        return None

# Sample a small portion of the DataFrame to reduce computation time and memory usage
sample_size = 100  # Specify the desired sample size
df_sample = df.sample(n=sample_size, random_state=1)

# Add ISO Alpha-3 country codes to the sampled DataFrame
df_sample["iso_a3"] = df_sample["Country"].apply(get_country_code)

# Remove rows with missing country codes
df_sample = df_sample.dropna(subset=["iso_a3"])

# Visualize Diabetes by Country
fig = px.choropleth(df_sample,
                    locations="iso_a3",
                    color="diabetes",
                    color_continuous_scale="YlOrRd",
                    title="Diabetes Prevalence by Country",
                    labels={"Diabetes": "Diabetes Prevalence"},)
                   # hover_name="Country")
fig.show()

# Visualize Heart Attack by Country
fig = px.choropleth(df_sample,
                    locations="iso_a3",
                    color="Heart Attack Risk",
                    color_continuous_scale="YlOrRd",
                    title="Heart Attack Risk by Country",
                    labels={"Heart Attack Risk": "Heart Attack Risk"},)
                    #hover_name="Country")
fig.show()
